  "prompt": "What is the present Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) of Nepal? What is the government doing to improve it?",
  "response": "As of the latest available data, the Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) in Nepal is approximately 25.2 deaths per 1,000 live births. It's important to note that this figure can change as new data becomes available, so it's advisable to consult the latest statistics from reliable sources such as the World Bank or the Nepalese government.\n\nThe government of Nepal, along with various international organizations, is actively working to improve the IMR through several initiatives, including:\n\n1. **Improving Maternal and Child Healthcare**: Implementing programs to provide better access to healthcare services for pregnant women and newborns, including prenatal and postnatal care.\n\n2. **Vaccination Campaigns**: Conducting widespread immunization programs to prevent common childhood diseases that contribute to infant mortality.\n\n3. **Nutrition Programs**: Promoting breastfeeding and providing nutritional supplements to combat malnutrition among infants and mothers.\n\n4. **Health Infrastructure Development**: Enhancing healthcare facilities, especially in rural and remote areas, to ensure that more communities have access to essential medical care.\n\n5. **Training Healthcare Workers**: Increasing the number of skilled healthcare professionals and providing them with the necessary training to improve maternal and infant health services.\n\n6. **Educating Communities**: Raising awareness about the importance of early and regular medical check-ups during pregnancy and proper newborn care practices.\n\nThese efforts are part of broader strategies to improve overall healthcare standards and outcomes in Nepal. For the most current initiatives and their impacts, it may be helpful to review official updates from Nepal's Ministry of Health and Population or international health organizations working in the region.",
